		<div class="about-screen-prose">
			<p>This project wields data from the <a href="https://ghslsys.jrc.ec.europa.eu/index.php">Global Human Settlement Layer</a>, which uses &ldquo;satellite imagery, census data, and volunteered geographic information&rdquo; to create population density maps.</p>
			<p>In parts of the world where census data is unreliable (e.g., India, China), population density was visibly noisy on the maps.</p>
			<p>Using this data for research purposes has a number of caveats, and most are very well detailed in <a href="https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/17445647.2017.1400476">this paper in the Journal of Maps</a> by Duncan Smith.</p>
			<p>The data is processed using Google Earth Engine (example script is <a href="https://code.earthengine.google.com/e9e22c289d4a9b3b3b0a39ecdfba261c">here</a>).</p>
			<p>The visualization was inspired by Alasdair Rae&rsquo;s <a href="http://www.statsmapsnpix.com/2016/10/the-global-human-settlement-layer.html">blog posts</a>, where he explained how to visualize snapshots of the data.</p>
			<p>A more detailed explanation of the data processing is <a href="https://blog.mapbox.com/3d-mapping-global-population-density-how-i-built-it-141785c91107?gi=35bb86de169a">here</a>.</p>
